SIMPLE: warren
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Warren
<hw>War"ren</hw> <pr>(w⟦ocr⟧r"r⟦ecr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>waresne</ets>, <ets>warenne</ets>, <ets>garene</ets>, F.
<ets>garenne</ets>, from OF. <ets>warer</ets>, <ets>garer</ets>, to
beware, to take care; of Teutonic origin; cf. OHG. <ets>war⟦omac⟧n</ets>
(in comp.), OS. <ets>war⟦omac⟧n</ets> to take care, to observe, akin to
E. <ets>wary</ets>. ⟦root⟧142. See <er>Wary</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Eng Law)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A place
privileged, by prescription or grant the king, for keeping certain
animals (as hares, conies, partridges, pheasants, etc.) called beasts
and fowls of <xex>warren</xex>.</def> <au>Burrill.</au> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>A privilege which one has in his lands, by royal grant or
prescription, of hunting and taking wild beasts and birds of
<xex>warren</xex>, to the exclusion of any other person not entering by
his permission.</def> <rj><au>Spelman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They wend both <qex>warren</qex> and in waste.</q> <rj><qau>Piers
Plowman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The <xex>warren</xex> is the next franchise in degree to
the park; and a forest, which is the highest in dignity, comprehends a
chase, a park, and a free warren.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A piece of ground for the breeding of
rabbits.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A place for keeping flash, in a river.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Warrener</ent>⟦br⟧
